The simulation design builds directly from similar prior work that compared statistical methods for evaluating the impact of state laws on firearms deaths (Schell et al. 2019) and opioid-related mortality (Griffin et al. 2021). In each simulation iteration, we first selected a random subset of k states to be the “treated” group that enacted both the primary and co-occurring policy, with the remaining states serving as the comparison group that never enacted either policy. Two time-varying policy indicators were generated denoting whether the primary policy (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
